properties.VIOLATION.INSPECTOR.COMMENTS: BASEMENT, APARTMENTS 1 AND 2 REAR - MISSING CARBON MONOXIDE DETECTORS.
properties.VIOLATION.ORDINANCE: Install carbon monoxide detector within 40 feet of every sleeping room in residential structure. (13-64-190, 13-64-210) A carbon monoxide detector is needed whenever there is a heating appliance on the premises that burns fossil fuel such as gas, oil, or coal, or air that is circulated through a heat exchanger. Install according to manufacturer instructions. A hard wired model requires an electrical wiring permit. In a single family residence, be sure the detector is on or below the lowest floor with a place to sleep. In a multiple dwelling residence heated by a boiler, install a detector in the same room as the boiler. Otherwise, each apartment follows single family guidelines. The owner is responsible for installation and written instructions, the tenant for testing, maintenance, and batteries.

properties.VIOLATION.ORDINANCE: Install carbon monoxide detector within 40 feet of every sleeping room in residential structure. (13-64-190, 13-64-210) A carbon monoxide detector is needed whenever there is a heating appliance on the premises that burns fossil fuel such as gas, oil, or coal, or air that is circulated through a heat exchanger. Install according to manufacturer instructions. A hard wired model requires an electrical wiring permit. In a single family residence, be sure the detector is on or below the lowest floor with a place to sleep. In a multiple dwelling residence heated by a boiler, install a detector in the same room as the boiler. Otherwise, each apartment follows single family guidelines. The owner is responsible for installation and written instructions, the tenant for testing, maintenance, and batteries.

properties.VIOLATION.INSPECTOR.COMMENTS: NO SMOKE DETECTOR
properties.VIOLATION.ORDINANCE: Install and maintain approved smoke detectors. (13-196-100 thru 13-196-160) Install a smoke detector in every dwelling unit. Install one on any living level with a habitable room or unenclosed heating plant, on the uppermost ceiling of enclosed porch stairwell, and within 15 feet of every sleeping room. Be sure the detector is at least 4 inches from the wall, 4 to 12 inches from the ceiling, and not above door or window.

properties.VIOLATION.INSPECTOR.COMMENTS: NO CARBON MONOXIDE
properties.VIOLATION.ORDINANCE: Install carbon monoxide detector within 40 feet of every sleeping room in residential structure. (13-64-190, 13-64-210) A carbon monoxide detector is needed whenever there is a heating appliance on the premises that burns fossil fuel such as gas, oil, or coal, or air that is circulated through a heat exchanger. Install according to manufacturer instructions. A hard wired model requires an electrical wiring permit. In a single family residence, be sure the detector is on or below the lowest floor with a place to sleep. In a multiple dwelling residence heated by a boiler, install a detector in the same room as the boiler. Otherwise, each apartment follows single family guidelines. The owner is responsible for installation and written instructions, the tenant for testing, maintenance, and batteries.

Install according to manufacturer instructions. A hard wired model requires an electrical wiring permit. In a single family residence, be sure the detector is on or below the lowest floor with a place to sleep. In a multiple dwelling residence heated by a boiler, install a detector in the same room as the boiler. Otherwise, each apartment follows single family guidelines. The owner is responsible for installation and written instructions, the tenant for testing, maintenance, and batteries.

properties.VIOLATION.INSPECTOR.COMMENTS: 2ND AND 3RD, MISSING CARBON MONOXIDE DETECTORS.
properties.VIOLATION.ORDINANCE: Install carbon monoxide detector within 40 feet of every sleeping room in residential structure. (13-64-190, 13-64-210) A carbon monoxide detector is needed whenever there is a heating appliance on the premises that burns fossil fuel such as gas, oil, or coal, or air that is circulated through a heat exchanger. Install according to manufacturer instructions. A hard wired model requires an electrical wiring permit. In a single family residence, be sure the detector is on or below the lowest floor with a place to sleep. In a multiple dwelling residence heated by a boiler, install a detector in the same room as the boiler. Otherwise, each apartment follows single family guidelines. The owner is responsible for installation and written instructions, the tenant for testing, maintenance, and batteries.

(13-64-190, 13-64-210) A carbon monoxide detector is needed whenever there is a heating appliance on the premises that burns fossil fuel such as gas, oil, or coal, or air that is circulated through a heat exchanger. Install according to manufacturer instructions. A hard wired model requires an electrical wiring permit. In a single family residence, be sure the detector is on or below the lowest floor with a place to sleep. In a multiple dwelling residence heated by a boiler, install a detector in the same room as the boiler. Otherwise, each apartment follows single family guidelines. The owner is responsible for installation and written instructions, the tenant for testing, maintenance, and batteries.

properties.VIOLATION.INSPECTOR.COMMENTS: BASEMENT AND SECOND FLOOR APT. MISSING SMOKE DETECTOR.
properties.VIOLATION.ORDINANCE: Install and maintain approved smoke detectors. (13-196-100 thru 13-196-160) Install a smoke detector in every dwelling unit. Install one on any living level with a habitable room or unenclosed heating plant, on the uppermost ceiling of enclosed porch stairwell, and within 15 feet of every sleeping room. Be sure the detector is at least 4 inches from the wall, 4 to 12 inches from the ceiling, and not above door or window.

properties.VIOLATION.INSPECTOR.COMMENTS: BASEMENT AND SECOND FLOOR APT. MISSING CARBON MONOXIDE DETECTORS.
properties.VIOLATION.ORDINANCE: Install carbon monoxide detector within 40 feet of every sleeping room in residential structure. (13-64-190, 13-64-210) A carbon monoxide detector is needed whenever there is a heating appliance on the premises that burns fossil fuel such as gas, oil, or coal, or air that is circulated through a heat exchanger. Install according to manufacturer instructions. A hard wired model requires an electrical wiring permit. In a single family residence, be sure the detector is on or below the lowest floor with a place to sleep. In a multiple dwelling residence heated by a boiler, install a detector in the same room as the boiler. Otherwise, each apartment follows single family guidelines. The owner is responsible for installation and written instructions, the tenant for testing, maintenance, and batteries.

properties.VIOLATION.ORDINANCE: Install carbon monoxide detector within 40 feet of every sleeping room in residential structure. (13-64-190, 13-64-210) A carbon monoxide detector is needed whenever there is a heating appliance on the premises that burns fossil fuel such as gas, oil, or coal, or air that is circulated through a heat exchanger. Install according to manufacturer instructions. A hard wired model requires an electrical wiring permit. In a single family residence, be sure the detector is on or below the lowest floor with a place to sleep. In a multiple dwelling residence heated by a boiler, install a detector in the same room as the boiler. Otherwise, each apartment follows single family guidelines. The owner is responsible for installation and written instructions, the tenant for testing, maintenance, and batteries.

properties.VIOLATION.INSPECTOR.COMMENTS: SUBMIT 2 COPIES OF A STRUCTURAL CONDITION REPORT PREPARED, SIGNED AND SEALED BY A LICENCED ARCHITECT OR STRUCTURAL ENGINEER, ATTESTING TO THE STRUCTURAL CONDITION OF THE BUILDING.EXISTING WOOD COLUMNS AND BEAMS AT BASEMENT.NEW STEEL SHORING POSTS AND STEEL BEAMS AT BASEMENT/FOOTINGS AND FOUNDATION.SECTION 13-196-030  STRUCTURAL STABILITY.   (A)   IF THERE IS ANY DOUBT AS TO THE STRUCTURAL STABILITY OF ANY BUILDING OR STRUCTURE, OR PARTS THEREOF, THE BUILDING COMMISSIONER MAY REQUIRE THE OWNER TO HAVE THE BUILDING OR STRUCTURE, OR PARTS THEREOF, TO BE EXAMINED BY A LICENSED ARCHITECT OR REGISTERED STRUCTURAL ENGINEER EMPLOYED BY THE OWNER, AGENT OR PERSON IN CHARGE, POSSESSION OR CONTROL OF ANY SUCH BUILDING, STRUCTURE, OR PART THEREOF.   (B)   THE OWNER SHALL SUBMIT A REPORT, IN WRITING, PREPARED AND SIGNED BY A LICENSED ARCHITECT OR REGISTERED STRUCTURAL ENGINEER, SHOWING THE STRUCTURAL CONDITION OF THE BUILDING, STRUCTURE OR PART THEREOF.  THE CONTENT AND FORMAT OF THE REPORT SHALL COMPLY WITH THE RULES AND REGULATIONS, AND TWO COPIES OF THE REPORT SHALL BE SUBMITTED TO THE BUILDING COMMISSIONER.  THE REPORT SHALL NOT BE CONSIDERED FILED UNTIL THE REPORT IS DETERMINED TO BE ACCEPTABLE BY THE BUILDING COMMISSIONER.   (C)   THE COMMISSIONER MAY ISSUE RULES AND REGULATIONS FOR THE ADMINISTRATION AND ENFORCEMENT OF THIS SECTION.

properties.VIOLATION.INSPECTOR.COMMENTS: APARTMENT #1- MISSING SMOKE DETECTOR.
properties.VIOLATION.ORDINANCE: Install and maintain approved smoke detectors. (13-196-100 thru 13-196-160) Install a smoke detector in every dwelling unit. Install one on any living level with a habitable room or unenclosed heating plant, on the uppermost ceiling of enclosed porch stairwell, and within 15 feet of every sleeping room. Be sure the detector is at least 4 inches from the wall, 4 to 12 inches from the ceiling, and not above door or window.

properties.VIOLATION.INSPECTOR.COMMENTS: APARTMENT #1,MISSING CARBON MONOXIDE DETECTOR.
properties.VIOLATION.ORDINANCE: Install carbon monoxide detector within 40 feet of every sleeping room in residential structure. (13-64-190, 13-64-210) A carbon monoxide detector is needed whenever there is a heating appliance on the premises that burns fossil fuel such as gas, oil, or coal, or air that is circulated through a heat exchanger. Install according to manufacturer instructions. A hard wired model requires an electrical wiring permit. In a single family residence, be sure the detector is on or below the lowest floor with a place to sleep. In a multiple dwelling residence heated by a boiler, install a detector in the same room as the boiler. Otherwise, each apartment follows single family guidelines. The owner is responsible for installation and written instructions, the tenant for testing, maintenance, and batteries.

properties.VIOLATION.INSPECTOR.COMMENTS: INSTALL CARBON MONOXIDE DETECTORS AT ALL LEVELS THROUGHOUT THE CONGRESS THEATER- THEATER OPERATING WITHOUT REQUIRED DETECTORS, DANGEROUS AND HAZARDOUS, PURSUANT TO ??13-64-190, 13-64-270 OF THE CODE.  A CARBON MONOXIDE DETECTOR IS NEEDED WHENEVER THERE IS A HEATING APPLIANCE ON THE PREMISES THAT BURNS FOSSIL FUEL SUCH AS GAS, OIL, OR COAL, OR AIR THAT IS CIRCULATED THROUGH A HEAT EXCHANGER. INSTALL ACCORDING TO MANUFACTURER INSTRUCTIONS. A HARD WIRED MODEL REQUIRES AN ELECTRICAL WIRING PERMIT. EVERY ROOM CONTAINING A BOILER REQUIRES A DETECTOR. EVERY FLOOR WITH FORCED AIR HEAT, CIRCULATED AIR FROM A HEAT EXCHANGER, OR A FOSSIL FUEL BURNING APPLIANCE REQUIRES 1 DETECTOR FOR EVERY 10,000 SQUARE FEET OR LESS
properties.VIOLATION.ORDINANCE: Provide carbon monoxide detector for every 10,000 sq feet or less on every floor of Class C Assembly Unit. (13-64-190, 13-64-270) A carbon monoxide detector is needed whenever there is a heating appliance on the premises that burns fossil fuel such as gas, oil, or coal, or air that is circulated through a heat exchanger. Install according to manufacturer instructions. A hard wired model requires an electrical wiring permit. Every room containing a boiler requires a detector. Every floor with forced air heat, circulated air from a heat exchanger, or a fossil fuel burning appliance requires 1 detector for every 10,000 square feet or less.

properties.VIOLATION.INSPECTOR.COMMENTS: SMOKE DETECTORS MISSING AT TOP OF STAIRS AND IN HALLWAYS IN THE RESIDENTIAL AREAS, AT 2121 N ROCKWELL DWELLING UNITS, DANGEROUS AND HAZARDOUS, PURSUANT TO ??13-196-100 THRU 13-196-160 OF THE CODE.  INSTALL A SMOKE DETECTOR IN EVERY DWELLING UNIT. INSTALL ONE ON ANY LIVING LEVEL WITH A HABITABLE ROOM OR UNENCLOSED HEATING PLANT, ON THE UPPERMOST CEILING OF ENCLOSED PORCH STAIRWELL, AND WITHIN 15 FEET OF EVERY SLEEPING ROOM. BE SURE THE DETECTOR IS AT LEAST 4 INCHES FROM THE WALL, 4 TO 12 INCHES FROM THE CEILING, AND NOT ABOVE DOOR OR WINDOW
properties.VIOLATION.ORDINANCE: Install and maintain approved smoke detectors. (13-196-100 thru 13-196-160) Install a smoke detector in every dwelling unit. Install one on any living level with a habitable room or unenclosed heating plant, on the uppermost ceiling of enclosed porch stairwell, and within 15 feet of every sleeping room. Be sure the detector is at least 4 inches from the wall, 4 to 12 inches from the ceiling, and not above door or window.

properties.VIOLATION.INSPECTOR.COMMENTS: CARBON MONOXIDE DETECTORS MISSING IN SEVERAL DIFFERENT LOCATIONS THROUGHOUT RESIDENTIAL SPACE, DANGEROUS AND HAZARDOUS, AT 2121 N ROCKWELL DWELLING UNITS, PURSUANT TO ??13-64-190, 13-64-210 OF THE CODE.  A CARBON MONOXIDE DETECTOR IS NEEDED WHENEVER THERE IS A HEATING APPLIANCE ON THE PREMISES THAT BURNS FOSSIL FUEL SUCH AS GAS, OIL, OR COAL, OR AIR THAT IS CIRCULATED THROUGH A HEAT EXCHANGER. INSTALL ACCORDING TO MANUFACTURER INSTRUCTIONS.  A HARD WIRED MODEL REQUIRES AN ELECTRICAL WIRING PERMIT. IN A SINGLE FAMILY RESIDENCE, BE SURE THE DETECTOR IS ON OR BELOW THE LOWEST FLOOR WITH A PLACE TO SLEEP. IN A MULTIPLE DWELLING RESIDENCE HEATED BY A BOILER, INSTALL A DETECTOR IN THE SAME ROOM AS THE BOILER. OTHERWISE, EACH APARTMENT FOLLOWS SINGLE FAMILY GUIDELINES.  THE OWNER IS RESPONSIBLE FOR INSTALLATION AND WRITTEN INSTRUCTIONS, THE TENANT FOR TESTING, MAINTENANCE, AND BATTERIES
properties.VIOLATION.ORDINANCE: Install carbon monoxide detector within 40 feet of every sleeping room in residential structure. (13-64-190, 13-64-210) A carbon monoxide detector is needed whenever there is a heating appliance on the premises that burns fossil fuel such as gas, oil, or coal, or air that is circulated through a heat exchanger. Install according to manufacturer instructions. A hard wired model requires an electrical wiring permit. In a single family residence, be sure the detector is on or below the lowest floor with a place to sleep. In a multiple dwelling residence heated by a boiler, install a detector in the same room as the boiler. Otherwise, each apartment follows single family guidelines. The owner is responsible for installation and written instructions, the tenant for testing, maintenance, and batteries.
